{"cursor":"609","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nUnder criminal law, a 'principal' is any actor who is primarily responsible for\na criminal offense. See, e.g., Superior Growers, 982 F.2d at 177-78; United\nStates v. Campa, 679 F.2d 1006, 1013 (lst Cir. 1982). Such an actor is\ndistinguished from others who may also be subject to criminal liability as\naccomplices, accessories or conspirators.\n","linknr":156,"url":"Principal_(criminal_law)","recorded":1362670655,"links":14,"instances":["crime","legal_term","commercial_law"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Legal terms"],"headings":["See also","Notes and references"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Scale_of_justice_2.svg/22px-Scale_of_justice_2.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["accessory","legal_term"],["conspiracy","crime"],["principal","commercial_law"]],"members":["conspiracy","accessory","principal"],"related":["Criminal_law","Accomplice","Accessory_(legal_term)","Conspiracy_(crime)","Principal_(commercial_law)"]}